Notes: The channels are arched so it should print without support. I didn't need a raft with ABS. The hex pattern gives a lot of structural stability just with the walls, so a light fill should do it. There is a tradeoff with number of shells. If you have gaps in the shell water could get inside, but if you use a lot of shells that will really up the plastic and print time. So I'd say 1 shell is risky if you're likely to have gaps. 2 shells probably is OK but depends on your printer. I printed with 3 shells and it came out great, but was a really long and heavy print by the time it was done.

description.text: This is a basic fan mount for a 40x40x10mm fan on a Robo3D which has been upgraded to a E3Dv6 hotend. Im using a derivative of this fan mount, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:491434 and the file is attached. It was opened up and cleaned up to allow for the maximum airflow available, despite it being mostly covered by the extruder mount. The shroud leaves about 1mm clear of the bed. The nozzle is designed to blow downward some and does not blow onto the Extruder nozzle. It has very little effect on the bed or extruder temps (less than 2 degree change from full off to full on). It was flow tested on the bed with talcum powder to check for proper draft flow. I will be using Noctua 40mm fan for its high flow and quiet operation, as well as good pressure ability since we are reducing the draft so much. M3x16 screws are recommended. I used 2 from the back of fan mount on bottom and 2 from front of fan shroud on top. You can enlarge the holes as necessary (currently all will thread a 3mm screw) to allow for easy assembly.

Here are two Christmas Ornaments made of pentagrams.

In one case the holes between pentagrams were filled with 60 equilateral triangles making a polyhedron - a small ditrigonal icosidodecahedron sometimes called a small triambic icosidodecahedron.  In the second case the pentagrams were made into slabs so that they formed a self supporting ornament.  
See the openSCAD code.
It should be possible to print both ornaments directly on the build surface.  The open ornament may need some cleaning up but is quite sturdy.

In Finland we have sauna. In sauna, we have kauha (ladle?) that is used for throwing water to the kiuas (hot rocks). Sauna + kauha = saunakauha.
Some time ago my (more traditional) wooden kauha went bad. Just introduced to the wonders of 3D printing and modeling, I decided to designed new one. Well, not the handle part, the printer I had at that time was way too small for printing long objects, so I reused the wooden handle from original kauha.
I used PLA, even though the temperature in finnish sauna is over 70 C minimum or it's not a real sauna. PLA isn't the best material as it's glass transition temp is around 60 C. But as long as the plastic is kept in saunakiulu (sauna waterbowl), it seems to be doing fine. Been doing fine for over a year now.
Better option would be ABS or PETG. I might design a handle for this since I now have a printer capable of printing objects up to 400m in height.

title: Nerf Rapidstrike Dual OLED Display Bracket
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This bracket replaces your Nerf Rapidstrike CS-18's upper sling mount with dual 128x64 OLED displays. 
Just print, add displays, open your Rapidstrike, remove the sling mount, and slot the bracket into place.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

20%

Notes: Use thick walls - I printed this with 2mm walls and 2mm top/bottom layers. I printed this in ABS, 0.4mm nozzle, 0.2mm layer height. Your mileage may vary. I recommend avoiding PLA for this print, because it's difficult to adhere the displays and it can become brittle in the cold. If you're using ABS, I recommend a raft. Because of the weird angles in the model, almost everything touching the bed will be support material.

These brackets are designed for common, inexpensive I2C-only SSD1306 breakouts. More complex breakouts, such as Adafruit's model and boards with a reset line, won't fit.
  • Disassemble your Rapidstrike and remove the upper sling mount.
  • Aggressively clean up your printed bracket. Remove all traces of support material, trim down any rough edges, and file off any over-extrusion. Test-fit your bracket in your blaster.
  • If your SSD1306 displays came with headers installed, desolder them.
  • Solder long wires to your displays and trim down the joints.
  • Move one display's address-selector jumper, so the displays have different I2C addresses.
  • Apply your adhesive of choice to the back of the upper display. I used 3M VHB tape.
  • Feed the upper display's wires through their hole on the bracket. Note that the displays are mounted upside-down.
  • Press the upper display into position.
  • Repeat steps 6, 7, and 8 with the lower display.
  • If necessary, wait for your adhesive to cure.
  • Gently slide the bracket into the blaster. It should fit identically to the stock sling mount point.
  • Route, trim, and prepare your wires. Because these displays use I2C, you can wire the displays in parallel.
  • Optional: Apply some Sugru or other rubberized material to the corners of the displays to protect against cracking.
I got the critical dimensions by cutting the Rapidstrike's upper sling mount into pieces, measuring them, and replicating them in SCAD.

description.text:
If you upgraded your Nerf Rapidstrike CS-18's pusher with a 180 motor, such as the MTB Hellcat, print this plate to cover it up! This motor cover prevents shorting and makes your blaster sexier. My version adds some unique features:
  • Extended plate also covers nearby cutouts for wire routing
  • Open design allows airflow into the motor
  • Provides a smooth panel for a nameplate, kill tally, owner name, etc
    • I included some text in the SCAD file, commented out from the uploaded STL. If you'd like to print a name directly onto the plate, just uncomment the line from the SCAD document, select a font, and re-render.

No

Notes: I highly, highly, highly recommend printing in ABS, since you can cement the cover plate directly to the blaster. For a beautiful finish, print directly on the plate with a nice, wide brim. Before installation, fully remove the brim and sand down any rough edges.

• Mod your blaster to accommodate the extended pusher motor.
  • Thoroughly sand the Rapidstrike CS-18 logo off the blaster, as well as the paint on its panel.
  • Optional: Sand the paint off of the area around your pusher motor cutout.
  • Mount your pusher in the blaster. This prevents adhesive from blocking the cutouts and helps you detect mistakes.
  • Test-fit the plate. Make sure the plate sits flat against the logo panel, the mounting pegs are touching the blaster, and that the motor is not touching the plate. If necessary, trim or sand the blaster or plate.
  • Throughly clean the cover plate and blaster. Brush with alcohol to remove dust and grease.
  • Prepare your adhesive. If you printed the plate in ABS, use ABS cement or plastic repair epoxy. If you printed in PLA or another material, use E6000.
  • Apply adhesive to the logo panel and both mounting pegs.
  • Press the panel into place, clamp securely, and allow adhesive to fully cure.
  • Optional: Apply a vinyl decal or use model paints to decorate the plate.

This is a tray for the player mats for the board game, Terraforming Mars! It's hard to keep all your counters on the right numbers, especially when there's so many cards being played and tokens moving every phase - so I whipped up a simple tray to hold your resource production tokens in place! Bonus - they have little slots on the side which are designed to hold the short end of a paperclip, for non-destructive attachment to the flimsy card play mats that the game comes with.   • print happily :D
  • from time to time - replace the content of the box (replace/clean sponge/cloth..)

These are sold at just about every hardware store for stabilizing tables, chairs, etc...  1/2" (13mm) pads will fit best.  I have found that they help the printer stay in place and also cut down even more on the vibration.  I also lengthened the channel that in placed inside the 2020 extrusion.  
Try printing them at 50-75% infill using PLA.  I have found that solid pieces almost offer too much support and reduce the dampening effect.  6 are needed for each printer.  Really helps cut down on the noise and vibration associated with delta-type printers!

This saw uses SCS8UU bearings and 8mm steel rods and a 25mm 12v 100rpm geared motor which i already had that's why i made this version. The base is 295x200x10mm (MDF) and am in the process of printing the other parts. This will take at least 50mm square items, the item shown in the vice is 4545 x 250mm. Other parts needed are 2 x 8mm (340mm) Steel Rods, 2 x 6mm (200mm) threaded rod), 3 x SCS8UU bearings, 1 rocker switch (19.5 x 13mm Hole), 1 Roller switch (KW11 3Z), 1 Hex motor coupler (4mm shaft), 2 x 100mm x 72 mm hinges, 1 DC 2.1mm panel mount socket. 2 x 6mm couplers or wingnuts, 1 x 4mm x 20mm threaded spacer or wingnut. 2 x 3mm Bolts (8mm Button Flanged) [Motor]
8 x 4mm Nuts and 20mm long bolts to mount the motor and base.
16 x 4mm Nuts and 16mm long Countersunk bolts for the hinges.
2x 4mm Nyloc Nuts with 25mm long bolts to fix the steel rods + 2 washers.
For the Hacksaw blade, 1 x 4mm x 20mm bolt, 1 x 4mm x 12mm bolt, 1 x 4 x 50mm bolt,2 x nyloc nuts and 1 x 4mm washer. To connect the motor to the blade assembly.
1x 4mm x 20mm bolt, 1 x 4mm nyloc nut, 2 x 4mm x 25mm penny washer.
10 x 4mm washers used as a bearing (see last picture)
1 x 6mm x 50mm bolt, 1 x 6mm washer and 1 nyloc flange nut. To connect the three SCS bearings and the green board.
12 x 4mm x 16mm bolts
3 x 4mm x 25mm bolts
2 x 4mm x 35mm bolts
5 x 4mm half nuts
3 x 4mm washers. The Vice mounted on the board takes 3 x 4mm x 35mm bolts, 3 x 4mm washers and 3 x 4mm nyloc nuts. 4 x 6mm half nuts to fix the stud. If the other vice is used. 3 x 4mm x 35mm bolts, 3 x 4mm washers and 3 x 4mm nyloc nuts. 6 x 6mm half nuts for the stud. (Changes)
Enlarged hole on "motor mount". The threads of the DC connector would not fit (see picture)
The 3mm x 6mm bolts for the motor interfered with the shaft coupler. These need to be changed to 3mm x 8mm (Max) Button Flange bolts. (See picture) (Changes 2)
Added packing pieces so that the blade is pushing level or down on the cutting stroke. Saw base V2 has new holes for this. Made a motor mount and clamp for a 37mm geared motor. Changed the drive piece to one with multiple holes, more power and a slower cut or a faster cut with less power. (Changes 3)
Remade "37mm motor mount" and "37mm motor clamp" (V2) and removed packing pieces.
This was to reduce some of the movement within the assembly. Use original saw base template. Made a motor base and switch mount for a 555 geared motor. Use original saw base template.
Made a printable hinge for the saw. This requires a 4mm steel rod 210mm long. The saw looks like some weight is needed to assist the cut. This can be bolted on the "bearing mount" using longer bolts.

comments.text: I think that it is complete now with some added weights bolted to it. I could not add any at the time i was cutting 4545 profile because they were 2 metre lengths and i had to lay them on the floor with carpet underneath. So the whole thing was bouncing a fair amount, which wasted a lot of the cutting energy. On the positive side the cut was nice and straight, much better than i could do by hand.

description.text: Here' a basic, parametric definition for toy wheels, created in Rhino + Grasshopper. The "axle" has a square shaft for assembly into whatever vehicle you dream up. The part is generated with a user-defined gap between the hub and wheel (0.4mm worked well for me). You can also include a through-hole to use a nail or screw for a more durable toy. In the included photo, I've used a small nail to lock in the 3D printed wheels. The nail does two things: (1) reinforces the plastic where the hub narrows to the plastic axle and (2) expands the axle section for a tighter fit into the hole. You could use glue, but I found that the nail does a great job of locking the wheels on. The reinforcing hardware allows you to use a much smaller axle size (that can stand up to enthusiastic toddlers). I used these wheels on my Modern Diesel Train. After assembling onto the train and hammering in the nails, I had to work the wheels back and forth to snap the 1st layer skin that occasionally binds the wheel in place. After breaking this loose, the wheels spins smoothly, with some resistance. One note: you may need to slightly oversize the central through-hole, in case your printer/slicer isn't completely accurate on ID dimensions.

title: Corner Bricks OpenSCAD Module Lego Angled Brick Builder

description.text: Corner Bricks is designed to create Lego-like bricks with a built-in angle. I needed these for L3-G0, my full size Lego R2-D2 (L3-G0 has a Blog and Youtube channel. L3-G0's main body consists of a barrel of 12 plates at 30 degree angles. I was using Lego hinges, which worked, but flex and weren't completely sturdy. So I made this library to create ~48 filler hinges to help L3-G0 keeps his shape. The lettering is just because I could, and to show it was originally designed for my L3-G0 robot. https://youtu.be/wdFkKSe0ZX0 shows some video of L3-G0 running around buying his own Lego Please support my designs
Sort of a random thing, but if you like my stuff please check out my Lego R2-D2's blog at http://L3-G0.com or L3-G0's Youtube, and please tweet of facebook a link to his page, every visitor helps!

CornerBricks is intended to allow you to create your own custom angles. I included a few STL files for 30, 60 & 120 degree angles, but you can do 42 degrees for your next thing if you want. CornerBricks depends on my FancyBricks library. See FancyBricks for instructions on tweaking it's "fudge" factors to get good fit between these bricks and Lego bricks on your printer. The included stuff was working on my FlashForge version of Replicator in ABS with 70C plate and 230C extruder. You may need to file the base or something if your printer mushes the first layer a bit fat. Skip the first steps if you've played with OpenSCAD and know how libraries behave.
  • Get OpenSCAD if you don't have it already, http://www.openscad.org/
  • Copy the FancyBricks.scad, CornerBricks.scad & font.dxf to some folder on your machine.
  • Either use a real library location, or to KISS, just make a new document and save it in the same folder as *.scad modules. (or just look at one of the other scad files).
  • Enter something like this into your OpenSCAD script (on the left)
    use <CornerBricks.scad>
    CornerBrick(2,2,30,1.0);
  • Press F5 (Design->Compile). You'll see an angled brick with 2x2 "wings" at a 30 degree angle with 1.0mm between the corners on top.
  • To make OpenSCAD create an STL file, you have to render it first, press F6 (Design->Compile and Render)
  • Design->Export the STL.
    • cornerbricks() is used to create an angled brick. The main inputs are:
  • length, which is the length of each wing (so length 2 at 0 degrees would be about a 4 long plate). default is 2.
  • depth, which is how wide the brick is, default 2.
  • angle, which is the angle between the two plates.
    • There are 2 more inputs to tweak things a little:
  • fudge, normally 0, which puts a space of fudge mm between the 2 corner plates.
  • hollow, normally true. Set it to false to have a flat "bottom". It prints faster and is a bit stronger without tubes on the bottom side, and L3-G0 doesn't need to stick stuff on the "bottom".
    • See my FancyBricks thing for more control over the brick shape. The stud size, wall thickness and other factors are all adjustable in fancybricks.scad if your bricks are too loose or too tight. These files print well on my FlashForge printer with my current ABS spool, using 230C extruder and 70C plate temps. My previous PLA seemed to print differently, so you may need to tweak things. Additionally, steep sides can make the studs droop, so you might need to tweak values, or use a file to trim them. My printer also "mushes" the brick onto the glass plate on the 1st layer, so you may need to trim something there as well. Support my designs please
Don't forget to take a look at L3-G0's Blog, he's the reason this library exists. Especially since he's complete now. Also he has video on YouTube. Please share & thumbs up and all that!

title: Fake Shock Reservoirs for the Traxxas Ultra Shocks

description.text:
So I designed these fake shock reservoirs for the traxxas ultra shocks
for my traxxas 2wd slash as a cosmetic upgrade as you see laid out here in the photos
to how to put them together and the finished product. If you wish to download this
file you will need sandpaper and some superglue and a Dremel power tool.

  • Depending upon your 3-D printer or service that you use to produce these parts
    you're going to need to sand out the parts to get the rough edges out to prepare them
    to be assembled.

  • After you got that done you should notice better yet in the STL File that I have made
    two kinds of circles one smaller and the other one bigger. The next thing that you will do here
    is to separate the ones that have a small circle from the other ones that have a bigger circle

  • After you got that done you will begin to assemble them by taking for example the top parts
    of the fake shock reservoirs in the bottom of the fake shock reservoirs that have
    smaller circles and assemble them as you see here in the photos.
    The fake shock reservoirs that have the smaller circle are for the front shocks.

  • After you're done with that you will begin to assemble the rear shock reservoirs that have
    the bigger circles better yet see in the STL File in the same way as you did with the front
    shock reservoirs. The shock reservoirs that have the bigger circles are going to be a bit longer
    and it will be for the rear shocks.

  • After you got that done you would take the mounts/spacer and glue on the front fake shock reservoirs
    unto the mount/spacer that is shorter in length glue on the fake front shock reservoir onto this smaller
    mount/spacer by using superglue as you see here in the photos will give you an
    idea how that is done.

  • After you're done with that you will take the fake shock reservoirs that had the bigger circle and glue it onto
    the mount/spacer that is longer in length also you will see in the photos how I did that.

  • After you're done with the assembly and sanding the fake shock reservoirs they should look like what you see in the photos.

  • Next of course remove the shocks off of your RC vehicle and clean them up and remove the stock spacer that is currently
    there on the front and rear shocks. And what you see in the photos will show you how to install the fake Shock Reservoirs
    onto the shocks themselves the photos will give you a good idea how to install them.

  • After you're done with the reassembling of your shocks of course for the shocks put them back onto your RC vehicle and you
    should get the and result as you see here in the photos.
    • so what I know at This point what this will work on the traxxas 2wd slash as you see here in the photos it does not get
    in the way of the body itself and it does not get in the way on how it performs. So I hope you enjoy this cosmetic upgrade.
